This new Sorter is useful for randomly shuffling tests in a Request class via the sortWith() method. The general usage would be
Request.classes(Class1.class, Class2.class, ..., ClassN.class).sortWith(Sorter.RANDOM.getComparator());

I find myself in need of randomly shuffling the test methods and classes to check that the tests do not depend on other tests. I could have implemented a Comparator which randomly outputs -1, or 1, but I wanted to perform an unbiased shuffle of the tests via Collections.shuffle(). I have not looked at the code for Collections.shuffle(), but I'm guessing it performs a Fisher-Yates shuffle.

I have also just run into the issue discussed at http://stackoverflow.com/questions/13050412/expect-exception-when-using-junit-theory

It would be useful if you could define theories like the below:

```java
@Theory(expected = SomeException.class)
public void shouldThrowAnExceptionForAllBadThings(Object thing) {
    assumeThat(thing, isBadThing())
    tryToPerformOperationWith(thing);
}
```
